# Lasso Regression

x = model.matrix(shares ~ ., news)[,-1]
y = news$shares



# This grid serves as a set of values of lambda to test. This range will cover all values
# of lambda necessary to produce ordinary least squares to the null model (Bo only).

grid = 10^seq(20, -2, length = 100)

ridge.mod = glmnet(x,y, alpha = 1, lambda = grid)





# Split data into train and test sets:

train = sample(1:nrow(x), floor(.7 * nrow(x)))
test = (-train)
y.test = y[test]

# Run the regression with cross-validation.

cv.out = cv.glmnet(x[train,], y[train], alpha = 1, lambda = grid)
plot(cv.out)

(bestlam = cv.out$lambda.min) # find the best lambda - 1*10^20
## [1] 5994.843
# Calculate the test MSE for this lambda.

ridge.pred = predict(ridge.mod, s = bestlam, newx = x[test,])
mean((ridge.pred - y.test)^2) 
## [1] 103573773
# Our lasso MSE is 192431675



# Now that we have the best lambda, refit the regression on the entire model to 
# obtain the coefficient estimates.

fin.ridge.mod = glmnet(x,y, alpha = 1)
predict(fin.ridge.mod, type = "coefficients", s = bestlam)

# Retry the lasso with a more restricted lambda.
set.seed(10)
news = read.csv("train_data.csv", header = T)
x = model.matrix(shares ~ ., news)[,-1]
y = news$shares

grid = 10^seq(1,2.5, length = 100)

ridge.mod = glmnet(x,y, alpha = 1, lambda = grid)





# Split data into train and test sets:

train = sample(1:nrow(x), floor(.7 * nrow(x)))
test = (-train)
y.test = y[test]

# Run the regression with cross-validation.

cv.out = cv.glmnet(x[train,], y[train], alpha = 1, lambda = grid)
plot(cv.out)

(bestlam = cv.out$lambda.min) # find the best lambda 
## [1] 46.41589
# Calculate the test MSE for this lambda.

ridge.pred = predict(ridge.mod, s = bestlam, newx = x[test,])
mean((ridge.pred - y.test)) 
## [1] -125.4548
actual.shares = news$shares[train]
plot((ridge.pred - news$shares[-train]), main = "Regression Residuals", ylab = "Residual")
abline(h=0, lty = 2, col = "white")

# Residuals are not normally distributed, regression conditions are not met.

Ridge regression and ordinary least Squares.

########### Ridge Regression


set.seed(10)
x = model.matrix(shares ~ ., news)[,-58]
y = news$shares

grid = 10^seq(-10, 1, length = 100)



# Split data into train and test sets:

train = sample(1:nrow(x), floor(.7 * nrow(x)))
test = (-train)
y.test = y[test]



cv.out = cv.glmnet(x[train,], y[train], alpha = 0, lambda = grid)
plot(cv.out)

(bestlam = cv.out$lambda.min) # find the best lambda
## [1] 1.668101e-09
# Calculate the test MSE for this lambda

ridge.pred = predict(ridge.mod, s = bestlam, newx = x[test,])
mean((exp(ridge.pred) - exp(y.test))^2)
## [1] 193575360
# Our ridge MSE is  193574888, 1.67e-09

# Now that we have the best lambda, refit the regression on the entire model to 
# obtain the coefficient estimates.

fin.ridge.mod = glmnet(x,y, alpha = 0,)
predict(fin.ridge.mod, type = "coefficients", s = bestlam)

# least squares

set.seed(10)
x = model.matrix(shares ~ ., news)[,-58]
y = news$shares


# Split data into train and test sets:

train = sample(1:nrow(x), floor(.7 * nrow(x)))
test = (-train)
y.test = y[test]
ols.mod = glmnet(x,y, alpha = 0, lambda = 0)
ols.pred = predict(ols.mod, s = 0, newx = x[test,])
mean((exp(ols.pred) - exp(y.test))^2)
## [1] 193575325

Stepwise Regression.

######################################## Try stepwise regression methods

null.model = glm(shares ~ 1 , data = news[train,])
full.model = glm(shares ~ . , data = news[train,])

# Perform forward selection.

step(null.model, scope = list(lower = null.model, upper = full.model), direction = "forward")
